{
  "global": "Determine the molecular formula of fully saturated X (MW=129, no oxygen) by testing heteroatom combinations, then use 13C (4 unique C) and 1H-NMR (4 unique H, protic solvent) symmetry constraints to resolve the specific constitutional structure.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Determine the molecular formula consistent with MW=129 and full saturation (DoU=0)",
      "atomics": [
        "Rule out pure hydrocarbon: CnH(2n+2)=129 gives 14n+2=129, n=9.07 (non-integer), so heteroatom required",
        "Test one nitrogen: fully saturated amine CnH(2n+3)N gives MW=14n+17=129, n=8 (integer) → candidate C8H19N",
        "Verify DoU for C8H19N: (2×8+2−19+1)/2=0, confirming full saturation",
        "Test other heteroatoms (S, Cl, P, 2N) to confirm none yield integer carbon counts at MW=129"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Enumerate C8H19N constitutional isomers with exactly 4 symmetry-distinct carbons",
      "atomics": [
        "List all acyclic C8H19N amine structural isomers (primary, secondary, tertiary)",
        "Count unique carbon environments in di-n-butylamine (n-Bu)2NH: C1=CH3, C2=CH2, C3=CH2, C4=N-CH2 → 4 unique carbons (both n-butyl chains equivalent by C2 symmetry)",
        "Verify competing isomers (diisobutylamine → 3 unique C; di-sec-butylamine → more complex; N,N-dimethylhexylamine → >4 unique C) are eliminated"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Confirm the structure using 1H-NMR in deuterated protic solvent giving 4 unique protons",
      "atomics": [
        "Identify that in a protic deuterated solvent (D2O or CD3OD), the exchangeable N−H proton undergoes H/D exchange and disappears from 1H-NMR spectrum",
        "Count observable 1H environments in di-n-butylamine after NH exchange: CH3 (δ~0.9), β-CH2 (δ~1.3), γ-CH2 (δ~1.5), N-CH2 (δ~2.4) → exactly 4 unique H signals",
        "Confirm tertiary amine alternatives (no exchangeable H) would still show only these 4 H environments for di-n-butyl geometry but tertiary amines don't fit the protic-solvent exchange clue"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Assign the final molecular identity with IUPAC name and formula",
      "atomics": [
        "Confirm di-n-butylamine: (CH3CH2CH2CH2)2NH, formula C8H19N, MW=8(12)+19(1)+14=129 g/mol",
        "State IUPAC name: N-butylbutan-1-amine (di-n-butylamine)"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Cross-check: MW=129 (odd) is consistent with exactly one nitrogen (odd-nitrogen rule for odd MW with C,H,N only)",
    "Sanity-check that 4 unique C (13C NMR) and 4 unique H (1H NMR after NH exchange) are simultaneously explained only by the C2-symmetric di-n-butylamine structure"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "Solve MW=129 with DoU=0 and no oxygen to get C8H19N, then use C2 symmetry of di-n-butylamine to match 4 unique 13C signals and 4 unique 1H signals (NH exchanged away in protic solvent).",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Solve 14n+17=129 for one-nitrogen fully saturated amine to get n=8, formula C8H19N",
        "atomics": [
          "Compute 14(9.07)≠integer for pure alkane, ruling out C,H-only structures",
          "Solve 14n+17=129 → n=8, confirming C8H19N as the unique one-nitrogen solution",
          "Calculate DoU=(16+2−19+1)/2=0, verifying full saturation",
          "Show that S (14n+34=129→non-integer), Cl (14n+36.5→non-integer), 2N (14n+32=129→non-integer) all fail"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Apply 4-unique-carbon constraint to select di-n-butylamine from C8H19N isomers",
        "atomics": [
          "List secondary amine isomers of C8H19N: di-n-Bu, di-i-Bu, di-sec-Bu, n-Bu/i-Bu mixed, etc.",
          "Count unique C in (n-C4H9)2NH: C1(CH3), C2(CH2), C3(CH2), C4(N-CH2) = 4, matching the NMR constraint",
          "Eliminate diisobutylamine (3 unique C: CH3, CH, N-CH2) and all other isomers with ≠4 unique C"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Apply protic-solvent 1H-NMR 4-unique-H constraint confirming NH exchange",
        "atomics": [
          "Note that D2O/CD3OD causes N−H → N−D exchange, removing NH signal from spectrum",
          "Count remaining 1H signals in di-n-butylamine: δ0.92 (CH3), δ1.33 (β-CH2), δ1.52 (γ-CH2), δ2.42 (N-CH2) = 4 unique H environments",
          "Confirm tertiary amines (no NH) also give 4 H in this scaffold, but tertiary C8H19N isomers have different carbon counts — secondary amine is uniquely consistent"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "State final answer: di-n-butylamine, (n-C4H9)2NH, MW = 8(12)+19+14 = 129 g/mol",
        "atomics": [
          "Write molecular formula C8H19N and verify MW=96+19+14=129 g/mol",
          "Assign IUPAC name N-butylbutan-1-amine (common name: di-n-butylamine)"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Apply odd-nitrogen rule: MW=129 (odd integer) with C,H,N composition requires an odd number of N atoms; one N is the minimal and only solution giving integer carbon count",
      "Verify simultaneously: 4 13C signals ↔ C2-symmetric n-Bu2NH; 4 1H signals ↔ same after N−H/D exchange in protic solvent — both constraints uniquely select di-n-butylamine"
    ]
  }
